Let $n$ be a positive integer, let $A, B$ be square symmetric $n times n$
matrices with real entries (so if $a_(i j)$ are the entries of $A$, the $a_(i
j)$ are real numbers and $a_(i j) = a_(j i)$). Suppose there are $n times n$
matrices $X, Y$ (with complex entries) such that $det(A X + B Y) != 0$. Prove
that $det(A^2 + B^2) != 0$ ($det$ indicates the determinant).
